":" from PostgresNIO. The functions are filled out with dummy code just now so the project will compile.","type":"text"}]}]},{"caption":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"I won’t go into any great detail about the SQL calls. That is not the purpose of this tutorial. We will cover how you construct, send calls and parse their results with ","type":"text"},{"code":"PostgresClient","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" as we proceed through the tutorial."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"code":"todos-postgres-12.swift","type":"step","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If we are going to be saving our todos to a database we are going to need a table to store them in."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"media":null,"code":"todos-postgres-10.swift","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Return to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"buildApplication(_:)"},{"text":" in Application+build.swift…","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"caption":[],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null},{"runtimePreview":null,"code":"todos-postgres-14.swift","type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Use the newly created ","type":"text"},{"code":"TodoPostgresRepository","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" and once the "},{"code":"PostgresClient","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" is running call ","type":"text"},{"code":"createTable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}],"caption":[],"media":null},{"runtimePreview":null,"code":"todos-postgres-23.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Update ","type":"text"},{"code":"buildRouter(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to take the repository as an argument and pass it to the controller."}]}],"caption":[],"type":"step","media":null},{"runtimePreview":null,"media":null,"caption":[],"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Back to TodoPostgresRepository.swift to start implementing our repository methods.","type":"text"}]}],"type":"step","code":"todos-postgres-12.swift"},{"caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Wait a sec! If you look closer that query looks like it’s got SQL injection. That’s a classic security issue. Except this isn’t the case here. The object being constructed is not a ","type":"text"},{"code":"String","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" but a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresQuery"},{"type":"text","text":" which uses "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"StringInterpolation"},{"type":"text","text":" to create parameter bindings for all the interpolated variables."}]}],"code":"todos-postgres-15.swift","media":null,"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To run a SQL query call "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresClient.query(_:logger:)"},{"text":" with the query string and a Logger`.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"caption":[],"media":null,"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"get"},{"type":"text","text":" method demonstrates how you get data returned from a query. The query returns a sequence of rows. You extract the data from the row by decoding it as a tuple. In this case there should only be one row so we return immediately as soon as we have it."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"runtimePreview":null,"code":"todos-postgres-16.swift","type":"step"},{"caption":[],"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"list","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is very similar to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"get"},{"type":"text","text":". Except there is no "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"WHERE"},{"type":"text","text":" clause in the SQL and we return all of the rows returned from the query instead of just the first."}]}],"code":"todos-postgres-17.swift","media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"type":"step"},{"type":"step","media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"patc